CRITICAL THINKING\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\sa200\sl360\slmult1\ul Introduction\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\sa200\sl360\slmult1\ulnone Critical thinking refers to the ability to think clearly, carefully, and reasonably about information, ideas, and situations before making judgments or decisions. It involves the use of logic, reasoning, and reflection in order to understand issues deeply rather than accepting them at surface level. Critical thinking encourages individuals to question assumptions, analyze arguments, evaluate evidence, and reach well-informed conclusions.\par
\par
In modern society, people are constantly exposed to information from different sources such as the media, the internet, social networks, schools, religious institutions, and political organizations. Not all information received from these sources is accurate or reliable. As a result, critical thinking has become a very important skill for students and members of society. It helps individuals to distinguish between facts and opinions, truth and falsehood, and strong and weak arguments.\par
\par
Critical thinking is not only useful in academics but also in everyday life. It influences how people solve problems, make decisions, relate with others, and respond to challenges. This work discusses argument analysis, evaluating evidence, types of critical thinking, bias and types of bias, influence of authority, objectives of critical thinking, evolution of critical thinking, and the benefits of critical thinking.\par
\par

